<br>
Here is the thing that is probably the funniest part about what is happening to the monks: so far the test server reports indicate they are taking the same DPS as before, meaning the soloing and exp group monks effectively have no change.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uargfeld.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Argfeld</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/14/02 11:44:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1402.topic&index=56>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_ale.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: it's not apples and oranges</span><hr size=1> DISCLAIMER:  I play a monk!<br>
<br>
(Pardon my excessive use of parentheses (I really mean that!!! (Seriously I do!)))<br>
<br>
I was personally very offended at Verant when Kunark came out and monks that wanted to dish out the most damage had to go get weapons to do it with.  Yes, I know that real-life oriental monks used all kinds of weapons (including swords and bows by the way!)  If I had my way, we'd go back to those days.  I think they should have offered monks a way to improve damage via skills (possibly ones that were quested for like the epic) and not by deluging us with weapons.  It was over a year after the release of Kunark that I finally broke down and stopped using my fists exclusively and started using weapons.<br>
<br>
Perhaps there are monks out there that out-tank warriors, but I am not one of them.  Unless the warrior is wearing a bunch of ghetto gear, he will out-tank me easily.  Unless he is sloppy and/or wearing ghetto gear, I will rarely get aggro off of him and will not keep it for long if I do.  My guild has done some North ToV stuff, killed Itraer Vius a few times, etc., but none of our monks can out-tank our warriors.  We have NEVER used a monk as a main assist on a raid unless all the warriors, SK's, and paladins have died and then we are almost certainly headed for a wipeout.  I tanked the Vindicator for 9 seconds once until my whirlwind discipline (riposte) expired and then I expired very quickly as well hehehe.  It did buy enough time for a real tank to get a CH chain going on him though.  I can tank if I have to in an XP group, but if there is a warrior or an SK or a paladin, I gladly give that job to him.<br>
<br>
None of our level 60 monks is within 1.5k hp of our level 60 warriors.  Just the other day, I found to my disgust that one of our enchanters was within 200 hp of me.  Then the other casters in the group chimed in with their hp totals which were almost as good.  Admittedly, I was two levels lower than all of them at 58, but it still kind of sucked.<br>
<br>
Yes, leather should not mitigate damage as well as plate.  However, the very high end stuff (which Verant screwed up with, I know) comes off of gods and dragons and the like.  Those of you that play D&amp;D know that such gear (were it accessible) tends to break all the rules.  A silk scarf off of a god might be tougher than that diamond coated titanium gorget you are so proud of.  The way they should have handled things (too late for it now though!) was to have made such items more class-specific.  Instead, they made almost all of the very best stuff in the game all/all.<br>
<br>
Regarding avoidance, monks have (and rightfully so!) the best in the game!  Seriously, think of all the types of fighters the world has seen, such as gladiators, foot soldiers, knights, and the like.  Which group does things like catching/dodging arrows, using acrobatic moves to avoid being hit, etc.?  It's the martial artist group of course!  That's what monks are based on!  In real life, the line between martial artists and warriors is not as clear and distinct as it is in EQ.  Think of samurai.  Are they warriors?  Yes!  Are they martial artists?  Also yes!<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, with some of the very toughest monsters in the game, avoidance becomes superior to mitigation for tanking.  So what does Verant do to fix this problem?  They nerf monk mitigation and make us slightly better at avoidance!  I know that a few people reading this still won't get it, so I'll explain.  This means that monks are going to become even better at tanking high-end monsters! <br>
<br>
*raps on skull of a Verant developer producing a hollow sound*<br>
&quot;Hello?  Anybody in there?&quot;<br>
<br>
Here is the way things are supposed to be.  This is the official stance of Verant (supposedly).  Of the three pure melee classes, Warrior, Monk, and Rogue, the Warrior is the standard.  Monks do more damage than warriors, but at the cost of having severe equipment and weight restrictions and fewer hitpoints.  Rogues do even more damage than monks, but can't take a hit worth crap.  I only mention this because an earlier poster seemed to think that warriors were supposed to do more DPS than monks.  If warriors did more damage than monks, there'd be no reason to play any melee class but warriors.<br>
<br>
An unfortunate side effect of this nerf comes from the fact that all raiding guilds MUST have pullers.  Even changing the game so as to make high-end encounters shorter will not remove the need for pullers.  Unless something changes, those pullers will be monks for the most part.  In order for a guild to be successful, these monks must be able to do their job right.  In order for them to do their job right, they will need the high end gear even more than they do already.  That means that the next time you (a warrior) want an item from NTOV, you are more likely than ever to lose it to a monk.  I'm not gloating.  I don't like this myself.  I don't want to be resented by my guildmates because of this.  <br>
<br>
How strong an effect will this have on pulling?  Will it make pulls take 10% longer or 20% longer or will it make them take 100% longer?  The mechanics of the game are too complicated to predict such a thing.  We'll just have to wait and see.  If the effect is extremely noticable, nobody, including those who cheered the monk nerf, will be pleased.  I can almost guarantee that if a pull is extremely difficult for your guild now, it may become impossible after the nerf.  If your monks die the first five times they attempt such a pull, and finally succeed with 150 hp left, what do you think is going to happen on that pull when we get nerfed?  You can kiss that encounter goodbye, at least until your guild powers up for a while.<br>
**********************************************<br>
On a side note, the changes to mod rods are going to force Mages to spend 99% of their time on raids making mod rods as opposed to the 75% of their time that they used to spend.  Mage do NOT like this change!  <br>
<br>
The MB nerf was necessary.  I would be upset if it hurt wizards going for xp and the like, but it doesn't.  It only hurts groups of wizards and not wizards individually.  It may hurt some guilds on raids, but sadly, our guild does not have enough wizards for that to be a factor with us.  Heck, at least one of the few wizards we have in our guild was pleased by this.  He had an intense dislike for what he called &quot;Team Manaburn&quot;.<br>
<br>
The CH change won't have that much of an effect on things.  If they had waited until PoP had been out a while and everyone was used to having CH's that completely healed the 10k hp warriors with one shot, then yes, people would be screaming in outrage.  With the current maximum hitpoints in the game, only the most uberly equipped warrior will even notice a difference.<br>
<br>
P.S.  You have now experienced first-hand an &quot;Argfeld Post&quot;.  If your eyes are bleeding, please seek medical attention.  You should be thankful.  This was actually one of my short ones. <p>Argfeld<BR>
Level 58 Monk<BR>
Order of the Scattered Winds<BR>
Bertoxxulous<BR>
